{
  "text": "Let G = (V, E) be an undirected graph. A (proper vertex) coloring of G is a surjective function \u03c3 : V \u2192 S such that xy \u2208 E implies \u03c3(x) = \u03c3(y). The minimum number |S| of colors such that there is a coloring of G is known as the chromatic number \u03c7(G). A greedy coloring of G is obtained by ordering the set of colors and coloring the vertices of G in a random order with the first available color. The Grundy number \u03b3(G) is the maximum number of colors required in a greedy coloring of G [CITATION_1] . Obviously \u03b3(G) \u2265 \u03c7(G). Determining \u03c7(G) [CITATION_2] and \u03b3(G) [CITATION_3] are NP-complete problems. A graph G is called well-colored if \u03c7(G) = \u03b3(G) [CITATION_4] . It is hereditarily well-colored if every induced subgraph is well-colored.",
  "citation_candidates": [
